I think a lot about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation able to build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because you couldn't easily determine that back then.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
Therefore, we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the series together.
That was completely different from today's streaming era, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches them whenever they feel like it, adding "spoiler warnings" to social media posts or discussing them in closed groups.
Unconsciously, we long for this universal community that once controlled everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," in which so many one-liners appeared that would be memes today.
We brought all these lines, and assumed that most of them already understood them.
Today, one cannot even assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There is too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Are we even going to get out of this oversaturation again?
We are trapped in a cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to realize later that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we must hold on to our nostalgia while at the same time accepting that the people who created the works we liked could also have made major mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on the feet of one person or another along the way.
Since our collective consciousness regarding media has faded, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who lift someone onto a pedestal, only to be shocked when they come crashing down.
We are in a phase of upheaval, and I am eager to see where it will ultimately lead.
Inclusion and safety should be the norm.
